data_description: daily aggregated case numbers provided in same repository by Center for Systems Science and Engineering of Johns Hopkins University
title_publication: Effective containment explains subexponential growth in recent confirmed COVID-19 cases in China
authors: Maier BF., Brockmann D.

name: secondary attack rate
method_description: Developed age-structured compartmental model; a modified SEIR framework with additional compartments for public health interventions, different severities of clinical symptoms, and risk of hospital admission
data_description: Contact data from POLYMOD study; comorbidity estimates by age from Canadian Community Health Survey for Ontario; COVID parameters derived from published studies; had 150 reported cases in Ontario on 19 Mar
title_publication: Mathematical modelling of COVID-19 transmission and mitigation strategies in the population of Ontario, Canada
authors: Tuite AR., Fisman DN., Greer AL.

name: growth rate

authors: Bliznashki S.

name: growth rate
method_description: Second simulation used logistic growth paradigm with weighted data points
data_description: Data of 75832 infectees from 4 March to 31 March
title_publication: A Bayesian Logistic Growth Model for the Spread of COVID-19 in New York
authors: Bliznashki S.

name: growth rate
method_description: Third simulation used same weighting scheme as second but assumed t-distribution and added two parameters

title_publication: A Bayesian Logistic Growth Model for the Spread of COVID-19 in New York
authors: Bliznashki S.

name: basic reproduction number

data_description: Used epidemiological data for Italy, mobility data, and population census data
title_publication: Spread and dynamics of the COVID-19 epidemic in Italy: Effects of emergency containment measures
authors: Gatto M., Bertuzzo E., Mari L., Miccoli S., Carraro L., Casagrandi R., Rinaldo A.

name: infection fatality rate
method_description: derive a relation to the true IFR from the reported CFR; use deaths over the true positive cases in the population, adjusted for false negative tests
data_description: compile comprehensive list of all countries that have recorded COVID-19 associated deaths as of April 21
title_publication: Estimating the Global Infection Fatality Rate of COVID-19
authors: Grewelle RE., De Leo GA.

name: infection fatality rate
method_description: Number of infected people was calculated by multiplying relevant population w the adjusted estimate of seroprevalence (or unadjusted if adjusted not available) - the analysis with maximal adjustment was selected. The number of deaths recorded at the time chosen by the authors of each study was selected - if no selection, number of deaths accumulated until after 1 week of mid-point of study period selcted. Inferred IFR was then obtained by dividing number of deaths by the number of infected people for the entire population and separately for people <70 years old. Values corrected for type of seroprevalence study performed (IgG, IgA, IgE, IgM)
data_description: Data are studies of seroprevalence of COVID-19 that have been done in general population or in samples that might approximate; only studies with at least 500 assessed samples were considered
title_publication: The infection fatality rate of COVID-19 inferred from seroprevalence data
authors: Ioannidis JPA.

Inferred IFR was then obtained by dividing number of deaths by the number of infected people for the entire population and separately for people <70 years old. Values corrected for type of seroprevalence study performed (IgG, IgA, IgE, IgM)
